>I agree with this statement
Which is why I think there are two distinct /hmofa/ camps
One needed their anthros to be heavily based off of the feral counterpart. The other would rather toss much of the feral behavior away if it gets in the way of the story they want to tell.
For the former, the social structure and the behavior of the feral side determines society and culture. It's an easy way to have most of your traits determined, but makes contradictions to that less likely.
For the latter, burying or subverting the animal behavior allows them to play with whatever culture their story needs at an expense. It's easy to lose readers when they miss small clues and then home in on 'a <species> waifur wouldn't act like that because I say so'

I'm more the latter, because the closer you get to the former the more it reeks of wanting a barely sapient girl. Humans can still act like dumb primates, but anyone worthy of love isn't the sum of their species' traits
